SIMPLE: colligate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Colligate
<hw>Col"li*gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Colligated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Colligating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>colligatus</ets>, p.
p. of <ets>colligare</ets> to collect; <ets>co-</ets> +
<ets>ligare</ets> to bind.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To tie or bind
together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pieces of isinglass are <qex>colligated</qex> in rows.</q>
<rj><qau>Nicholson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Logic)</fld> <def>To bring together by colligation;
to sum up in a single proposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had discovered and <qex>colligated</qex> a multitude of the
most wonderful . . . phenomena.</q> <rj><qau>Tundall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Colligate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Colligate
<hw>Col"li*gate</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Bound together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Colligation</ent>⟦br⟧
